#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:2
msgid "Getting to know the MidiGurdy"
msgstr "Kennenlernen der MidiGurdy"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:4
msgid ""
"In many ways the MidiGurdy works very similar to other hurdy-gurdies, but"
" there are a few differences that you should be aware of. The MidiGurdy "
"also offers many functions that you won‘t find on an acoustic instrument,"
" which this manual will explain in detail."
msgstr ""
"In vielerlei Hinsicht funktioniert die MidiGurdy sehr ähnlich wie andere "
"Drehleiern, aber es gibt ein paar Unterschiede, die beachtet werden sollten. "
"Außerdem bietet die MidiGurdy viele Funktionen, die Sie bei einem "
"akustischen Instrument nicht finden werden und die in diesem Handbuch "
"ausführlich erläutert werden."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:9
msgid ""
"In this section we will explore the mechanical features of the instrument"
" and learn about the user controls and the connectors available on the "
"MidiGurdy."
msgstr ""
"In diesem Abschnitt werden wir die mechanischen Eigenschaften des "
"Instruments untersuchen und mehr über die Bedienelemente und die Anschlüsse "
"der MidiGurdy erfahren."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:13
msgid "Mechanical Features"
msgstr "Mechanische Eigenschaften"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:20
msgid "The mechanical features of the MidiGurdy"
msgstr "Die mechanischen Eigenschaften der MidiGurdy"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:23
msgid "(1) Keyboard"
msgstr "(1) Tastatur"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:25
msgid ""
"The keyboard of the MidiGurdy works like most hurdy-gurdies and uses "
"gravity for the keys to fall back into their original position. This "
"requires you to tilt the instrument forward while playing."
msgstr ""
"Die Tastatur der MidiGurdy funktioniert wie die der meisten anderen "
"Drehleiern und nutzt die Schwerkraft, damit die Tasten in ihre ursprüngliche "
"Position zurückfallen. Dies erfordert, dass Sie das Instrument während des "
"Spielens nach vorne neigen."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:30
msgid "(2) Tangent box lid"
msgstr "(2) Tangentenkastendeckel"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:32
msgid ""
"The tangent is covered by a wooden lid that is held in place using four "
"magnets."
msgstr ""
"Der Tangentenkasten hat einen hölzernen Deckel der mit Hilfe von vier "
"Magneten festgehalten wird."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:36
msgid "(3) Crank"
msgstr "(3) Kurbel"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:38
msgid ""
"The crank also works like you would expect from a hurdy-gurdy. You can "
"turn it forwards, backwards, shake it and use it to sound the trompette "
"by giving shorter or longer impulses while turning. The turning speed "
"also affects the volume of the instrument."
msgstr ""
"Die Kurbel funktioniert ebenfalls wie bei jeder anderen Drehleier. Sie kann "
"vorwärts und rückwärts gedreht werden, Impulse während des Drehens lösen die "
"Schnarrgeräusche aus. Die Drehgeschwindigkeit beeinflusst außerdem die "
"Lautstärke des Instruments."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:44
msgid "(4) Wheel Cover"
msgstr "(4) Radschutz"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:46
msgid ""
"The wheel cover can be lifted by grabbing it on both sides and simply "
"lifting it upwards with a little force.  Once the cover is removed, you "
"can grab the wheel to attach or remove the crank.  To close the cover "
"again, carefully insert it into the cut-out around the wheel and push "
"down with a little force until you hear it snap into place."
msgstr ""
"Die Radabdeckung kann angehoben werden, indem man sie auf beiden Seiten "
"greift und sie mit etwas Kraft einfach nach oben hebt.  Sobald die Abdeckung "
"entfernt ist, können Sie das Rad festhalten, um die Kurbel anzubringen oder "
"zu entfernen.  Um die Abdeckung wieder zu schließen, stecken Sie sie "
"vorsichtig in den Ausschnitt um das Rad herum und drücken Sie sie mit etwas "
"Kraft nach unten, bis sie hörbar einrastet."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:53
msgid "(5) Wheel Brake Control"
msgstr "(5) Radbremse"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:55
msgid ""
"The black knob right next to the wheel cover controls the wheel brake. It"
" is used to adjust the amount of resistance that you feel while turning "
"the crank, simulating strings pressing down onto the wheel. Turn right to"
" pull it tighter and increase the required force, turn left to loosen the"
" brake and reduce the required force.  Always turn the crank while "
"adjusting the brake to avoid overloading the wheel and axle! Excessive "
"force on the brake might damage the parts of the braking system."
msgstr ""
"Der schwarze Drehknopf direkt neben der Radabdeckung steuert die Radbremse. "
"Sie wird verwendet, um den Widerstand einzustellen, den Sie beim Drehen der "
"Kurbel spüren, und simuliert den Andruck von Saiten auf dem Rad. Drehen Sie "
"den Drehknopf rechts, um die Bremse anzuziehen und die erforderliche Kraft "
"zum Drehern der Kurbel zu erhöhen. Drehen Sie den Drehknopf nach links, um "
"die Bremse zu lösen und die erforderliche Kraft zu reduzieren.  Drehen Sie "
"immer die Kurbel, während Sie die Bremse einstellen, um eine Überlastung von "
"Rad und Achse zu vermeiden! Eine zu hohe Kraft auf der Bremse kann die Teile "
"des Bremssystems beschädigen."

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:64
msgid "(6) Front panel connectors"
msgstr "(6) Anschlüsse"

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:66
msgid ""
"The front panel contains all connectors used to interface the MidiGurdy "
"with external components.  We will have a closer look at the individual "
"input and output ports in the next section.  Instrument strap pins There "
"are three instrument strap pins: one at the front and two pins at the "
"back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:73
msgid "Tangent box lid buttons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:75
msgid ""
"There are two distinct sections that are used to control the many "
"different functions of the MidiGurdy: the five buttons in the tangent box"
" lid and the main user interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:83
msgid "Buttons in the tangent box lid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:85
msgid ""
"The lid of the tangent box contains five buttons, arranged in two groups."
" Let’s look at the group of three buttons closest to the player first, "
"called the “String Buttons“."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:90
msgid "The String Buttons (S1 S2 S3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:92
msgid ""
"These buttons are used to switch individual strings on and off (lift them"
" on and off the wheel). The order of the buttons follows the string "
"positions on an acoustic hurdy-gurdy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:96
msgid "**S1** drone string (closest to the keyboard)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:98
msgid "**S2** melody string (centre)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:100
msgid "**S3** trompette string (closest to the player)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:103
msgid ""
"Press any of these buttons, turn the crank and notice how the string "
"sound gets switched on or off. An illuminated button means the string is "
"currently switched on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:108
msgid "The Group Buttons (G2 G3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:110
msgid ""
"The two black buttons on the tangent box lid are called the “Group“ "
"buttons. The MidiGurdy has a total of nine strings but only three String "
"Buttons for switching the strings on and off. This is why the Strings are"
" arranged in three groups:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:115
msgid "Group 1 – Drone 1, Melody 1, Trompette 1 (activated by default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:117
msgid "Group 2 – Drone 2, Melody 2, Trompette 2 ( activated with **G2**)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:119
msgid "Group 3 – Drone 3, Melody 3, Trompette 3 (activated with **G3**)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:121
msgid ""
"If you only press the String Buttons **S1**, **S2** or **S3** you are "
"controlling the strings in **Group 1**, as this group is active by "
"default (i.e. if you don’t press any of the Group Buttons.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:124
msgid ""
"If you want to control the strings in **Group 2** instead, you simply "
"hold the **G2** button while pressing any of the String Buttons. Or hold "
"the **G3** button while pressing the String Buttons to control the "
"strings in **Group 3**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:128
msgid ""
"As soon as you press one of the Group Buttons, the illumination of the "
"String Buttons changes to indicate the on/off state of the drone, melody "
"and trompette string in that group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:132
msgid ""
"Pressing the Group Buttons only affects which strings you switch on and "
"off with the String Buttons.  They have no other effect on the "
"instrument.  You can mix and match strings from all groups while playing,"
" or even play all nine strings simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:139
msgid "User Interface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:145
msgid "The main user interface of the MidiGurdy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:147
msgid ""
"The main user interface of the MidiGurdy consists of the display, a "
"rotary knob and five buttons.  First a short overview explaining the most"
" important functions of the interface. For a detailed description of the "
"settings and the menu system, please see the section :ref:`menu-system`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:153
msgid "Display"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:155
msgid ""
"The display of the MidiGurdy is used to show you the current setup of the"
" instrument and is used to display all settings and menu items. By "
"default it shows the so called “Home Screen“ which informs you about the "
"current tuning and on/off state of all strings, the currently selected "
"preset, how the instrument is powered and the estimated battery charge in"
" case you are running on batteries (see :ref:`menu-system` for more "
"details)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:163
msgid "Rotary knob (ROT)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:165
msgid ""
"You can turn this knob left and right and also press it like a button.  "
"Turning the knob is used to navigate the menu system or to increase or "
"decrease values. Pressing the knob usually selects a menu item or "
"confirms a changed value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:170
msgid "Back button (BACK)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:172
msgid ""
"The back button is right next to the rotary knob. Regardless on where you"
" are in the menu system, pressing this button will always cancel the "
"current selection or operation, bring you back to the previous screen and"
" eventually back to the Home screen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:178
msgid "Display Buttons (D1 D2 D3 D4)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:180
msgid ""
"The four buttons under the display are called the “Display Buttons” and "
"activate different functions depending on the currently active menu. By "
"default, the first three buttons activate the configuration menus for"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:184
msgid "the drone strings **D1**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:185
msgid "the melody strings **D2**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:186
msgid "the trompette string **D3**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:188
msgid "as indicated by their labels in the display on the Home Screen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:190
msgid ""
"The rightmost button **D4** is also called the “Power / Settings” button."
"  As the name suggests, this button is used for multiple purposes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:193
msgid "Switching the MidiGurdy on and off:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:195
msgid "Hold this button for about 1 second to switch the instrument on"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:197
msgid "Hold this button for about 4 seconds to switch the instrument off again"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Getting_to_know_the_MidiGurdy.rst:199
msgid ""
"Hold this button for about 8 seconds and release it again to do a forced "
"restart of the instrument. Use this if the MidiGurdy has locked up and "
"doesn't react to any user input any more (which hopefully will never "
"happen!)"
msgstr ""

